{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8d07497d-ab2b-4c70-a9c4-bb7029ca944b","content":"## What Happened\n\nC# 14 introduces **first-class implicit span conversions** in overload resolution. Now `array.Contains(num)` on an `int[]` resolves to:\n\n```\nMemoryExtensions.Contains<int>(ReadOnlySpan<int>, int)\n```\n\ninstead of the .NET 9 resolution:\n\n```\nEnumerable.Contains<int>(IEnumerable<int>, int)\n```\n\nThe expression tree interpreter (`preferInterpretation: true`) cannot invoke a method that takes `ReadOnlySpan<T>` — ref structs can't be passed through the reflection-based invocation the interpreter uses, so it throws at runtime.\n\n## Fix\n\nForce resolution back to `Enumerable.Contains` by casting the array to `IEnumerable<int>`:\n\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);\n```\n\nOr call the method explicitly (non-extension style):\n\n```csharp\nExpression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =\n    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);\n```\n\nBoth approaches bypass the span-preferring overload resolution and keep the expression tree representable and interpretable.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"11b979ab-6ae9-4ba5-8fad-6944598649b3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a breaking change in .NET 10 / C# 14 related to LINQ expression trees and the `.Contains()` method on arrays.\n\nLet me think about what changed in .NET 10 that would cause this issue.\n\nIn .NET 10, there's a breaking change related to how the C# compiler resolves extension methods. In C# 14 (which ships with .NET 10), the compiler introduces **extension types** (formerly \"roles and extensions\") or more relevantly, there's a change in how `Enumerable.Contains()` vs the array's own methods are resolved.\n\nActually, let me think more carefully. \n\nThe real issue seems to be about how the compiler resolves `array.Contains(num)` in .NET 10 — it might be picking a different